## Lesson 52-3: Question 24 (Author Attitude)

### Before the Explanation heading
{{+**Try this:** Attempt the question before reading the analysis below.+}}

### After the Question Breakdown heading
{{+**Question Type: Author Attitude.** Find the specific words the author uses to describe 18th-century lawyers. Are they neutral, positive, or negative? How strong is the language? Calibrate between mild criticism and outright contempt.+}}

### After the (D) analysis
{{!note!}} The (B) vs. (D) distinction is the key teaching moment here. Both are negative, but "critical" (measured, academic disapproval) is milder than "scornful" (open contempt). LSAT Attitude questions almost always avoid the extreme end of the scale. Teach students to default to the moderate option unless the passage uses openly hostile language.

## Lesson 52-4: Question 25 (Reference/Purpose)

### Before the Explanation heading
